        "user": "What is a lexical reachability?",
        "assistant": "# Lexical Reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is a concept primarily from program analysis and language theory, used to determine whether one point in a program (or one node in a graph) can \"reach\" another according to a context-sensitive grammar of valid paths.\n\n## The Core Idea\n\nIn a standard graph, *reachability* just asks: \"Is there any path from node A to node B?\"\n\n**Lexical reachability** (often more formally called **CFL-reachability**, for Context-Free Language reachability) restricts this question: a path from A to B only counts if the sequence of edge labels along the path forms a string in some specified context-free language.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. **Label the edges** of a graph with symbols (e.g., from an alphabet representing operations like \"call,\" \"return,\" \"field-access,\" etc.).\n2. **Define a context-free grammar** describing which sequences of labels are \"valid.\"\n3. Node *B* is **lexically reachable** from node *A* if and only if there exists a path from *A* to *B* whose concatenated edge labels form a string derivable by the grammar.\n\nA classic example uses balanced parentheses: a path is valid only if `(` symbols are properly matched with `)` symbols. This naturally captures things like matched function calls and returns.\n\n## Why It Matters\n\nLexical/CFL-reachability is the standard formal foundation for many static analyses:\n\n- **Interprocedural dataflow analysis** — matching calls with returns so analysis doesn't follow infeasible paths (e.g., entering function `f` from one call site but returning to a different one).\n- **Pointer/alias analysis** — Andersen-style and field-sensitive analyses are often phrased as CFL-reachability problems.\n- **Program slicing** — finding statements that influence a given variable.\n- **Type-based analyses** — checking subtyping or flow constraints.\n\n## Complexity\n\nGeneric CFL-reachability over a graph with *n* nodes can be solved in roughly **O(n³)** time, which is a well-known bound (and recent work has shown it's hard to improve substantially in the worst case).\n\n## Related Variants\n\n- **Dyck-reachability** — a special case where the language is the Dyck language (balanced parentheses); very common in practice.\n- **L-reachability** — the same idea generalized to any formal language *L*.\n- **InterDyck-reachability** — combining multiple Dyck languages, useful when you want to match both calls/returns and field reads/writes simultaneously.\n\nWere you asking about this in the context of a specific area (compilers, program analysis, graph theory)? I can tailor the explanation further.",
