        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
        "assistant": "# Lexical Reachability vs. Vocabulary Coverage\n\nThese are two quite different concepts that happen to share the word \"lexical\" — they come from different fields and answer different questions.\n\n## Lexical Reachability (Program Analysis / Graph Theory)\n\nAs described earlier, this is about **paths in a graph** being valid according to a formal grammar:\n\n- **Domain:** Compilers, static analysis, formal language theory.\n- **Question answered:** \"Can I get from node A to node B via a path whose edge labels form a valid string in language L?\"\n- **Objects involved:** Graphs, edges, labels, context-free grammars.\n- **Use cases:** Interprocedural dataflow, alias analysis, slicing.\n\n## Vocabulary Coverage (Linguistics / NLP / Language Pedagogy)\n\nThis is a **statistical measure** about how much of a text (or corpus) a given vocabulary list accounts for:\n\n- **Domain:** Corpus linguistics, second-language acquisition, NLP.\n- **Question answered:** \"What percentage of the words (tokens) in this text are contained in my vocabulary list?\"\n- **Objects involved:** Word lists, texts, token/type counts.\n- **Use cases:**\n  - Estimating reading difficulty (e.g., learners typically need ~95–98% coverage for comprehension).\n  - Designing graded readers and language curricula.\n  - Evaluating tokenizer or embedding vocabularies in NLP models (out-of-vocabulary rates).\n\n## Key Differences at a Glance\n\n| Aspect | Lexical Reachability | Vocabulary Coverage |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Field** | Program analysis, formal languages | Linguistics, NLP, pedagogy |\n| **Type of concept** | Structural / relational (yes/no for paths) | Statistical / quantitative (a percentage) |\n| **\"Lexical\" refers to** | Symbols/labels along edges (lexemes of a formal language) | Words/lexical items of a natural language |\n| **Underlying math** | Graph theory + context-free grammars | Frequency counting over corpora |\n| **Typical output** | A reachability relation (set of node pairs) | A coverage percentage |\n\n## Why the Confusion?\n\nBoth terms use \"lexical\" because they involve **symbols drawn from a defined set** — but in lexical reachability the \"lexicon\" is an alphabet of edge labels in a formal grammar, whereas in vocabulary coverage the \"lexicon\" is a list of words from a natural language.\n\nThey aren't really competing concepts; they belong to different worlds and are rarely mentioned in the same context.\n\nDid you encounter these terms together somewhere? If you tell me the context, I can clarify which one is more relevant — or whether some hybrid usage (e.g., in NLP) is being meant.",
