        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from graph reachability?",
        "assistant": "Same caveat as before: I'm answering *given* the definition you supplied for \"lexical reachability,\" which I still don't treat as canonical. With that on the table:\n\n## Graph Reachability\n\n- A **structural, binary** property of a graph.\n- Asks: *\"Does there exist a path from node A to node B following the edges?\"*\n- Properties:\n  - Defined over an explicit graph (nodes + edges).\n  - Typically yes/no (or shortest-path length).\n  - Purely combinatorial — no notion of \"confidence,\" \"distinguishability,\" or \"context.\"\n  - Symmetric concept across all node pairs (same algorithm applies).\n- Variants like **CFL-reachability** add a constraint that the path's edge-label sequence belong to a formal language, but the core question is still *path existence*.\n\n## Lexical Reachability (per your definition)\n\n- A **behavioral, scalar/continuous** property of a model.\n- Asks: *\"How much does a single in-context definition shift the model's ability to discriminate a term from its near-neighbors?\"*\n- Properties:\n  - No explicit graph — the \"substrate\" is a model's internal representations and output distributions.\n  - Produces a **gap / delta** (cold-state vs. post-definition), not a path.\n  - Inherently **relational to near-neighbors**, not to arbitrary targets.\n  - **Model-dependent** — the same term has different reachability across models.\n  - Tied to **context-time intervention** (the single-sentence definition), which has no analog in graph reachability.\n\n## Where They Could Be Made to Look Similar (and Why It's Misleading)\n\nYou could *try* to cast lexical reachability in graph terms — e.g., nodes = terms, edges = distinguishability, and \"reachability\" = whether a definition-edge connects a confused pair to a discriminated state. But this analogy strains quickly:\n\n- Graph reachability is about **existence of a path**; your lexical reachability is about **magnitude of a behavioral shift**.\n- Graph reachability is **deterministic and structural**; lexical reachability is **probabilistic and empirical**.\n- The \"single-sentence definition\" isn't really an edge — it's an intervention whose effect is what's being measured.\n\n## Bottom Line\n\nThey share the word \"reachability\" but the underlying question is different:\n- **Graph reachability:** *Can you get from here to there?*\n- **Lexical reachability (as you've defined it):** *How much does defining a term in context improve the model's ability to tell it apart from things it resembles?*\n\nThe shared term is more metaphorical than technical. If anything, your definition is closer in spirit to concepts like **in-context learning gain**, **probing accuracy delta**, or **calibration improvement under definition priming** than to anything in the reachability literature.\n\nStill happy to push on the definition itself if you want — e.g., I'm curious whether you intend \"distinguishability\" to mean something like KL divergence between output distributions, embedding cosine distance, classification accuracy on a forced-choice task, or something else. The answer materially changes what the metric captures.",
